defs.name: TrieKey
defs.docs: Trait for types which can be used to key a Radix Trie.

attributes.value: / Trait for types which can be used to key a Radix Trie.
/ Types that implement this trait should be convertible to a vector of half-bytes (nibbles)
/ such that no two instances of the type convert to the same vector.
/ To protect against faulty behaviour, the trie will **panic** if it finds two distinct keys
/ of type `K` which encode to the same `Nibblet`, so be careful!
/ If you would like to implement this trait for your own type, you need to implement
/ *either* `encode_bytes` or `encode`. You only need to implement one of the two.
/ If you don't implement one, your code will **panic** as soon you use the trie.
/ There is no performance penalty for implementing `encode_bytes` instead of `encode`,
/ so it is preferred except in the case where you require half-byte precision.
/ Many standard types implement this trait already. Integer types are encoded *big-endian*
/ by default but can be encoded little-endian using the `LittleEndian<T>` wrapper type.

defs.name: get_ancestor
defs.value:
pub fn get_ancestor<'a, Q: ?Sized>(&'a Self, &Q) -> Option<SubTrie> where
K: Borrow<Q>, Q: TrieKey
defs.docs: Fetch a reference to the closest ancestor node of the given key.

attributes.value: / Fetch a reference to the closest ancestor node of the given key.
/ If `key` is encoded as byte-vector `b`, return the node `n` in the tree
/ such that `n`'s key's byte-vector is the longest possible prefix of `b`, and `n`
/ has a value.
/ Invariant: `result.is_some() => result.key_value.is_some()`.
/ The key may be any borrowed form of the trie's key type, but TrieKey on the borrowed
/ form *must* match those for the key type.
inline

defs.name: Trie
defs.docs: Data-structure for storing and querying string-like keys and associated values.

attributes.value: / Data-structure for storing and querying string-like keys and associated values.
/ Any keys which share a common *prefix* are stored below a single copy of that prefix.
/ This saves space, and also allows the longest prefix of any given key to be found.
/ You can read more about Radix Tries on [Wikipedia][radix-wiki].
/ Lots of the methods on `Trie` return optional values - they can be composed
/ nicely using `Option::and_then`.
/ [radix-wiki]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix_tree

attributes.value: / Wrapper for subtrie lookup results.
/ When fetching from a subtrie, if the prefix is wrong you'll get an `Err(())`.
/ Otherwise you'll get an `Ok(_)`, where the contained option value is what would ordinarily
/ be returned by get/insert/whatever.
